---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const lastUpdated = '2026-05-25';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Refund Policy — Wyreup"
  description="When you can get a refund on Wyreup credits and how to request one."
>
  <article class="legal">
    <header>
      <h1>Refund Policy</h1>
      <p class="meta">Last updated: {lastUpdated}</p>
    </header>

    <h2>The short version</h2>
    <p>
      Unused credits are refundable within 30 days of purchase. Used
      credits are not, except in cases of clear product malfunction on
      our end. A refund under this policy is your sole financial remedy
      for the credits in question — see section 8 of the
      <a href="/legal/terms">Terms of Service</a> for the overall
      limitation of liability.
    </p>

    <h2>Unused credits — 30-day refund</h2>
    <p>
      If you purchased credits in the last 30 days and you have at least
      as many credits in your account as you purchased in that order, we
      will refund that order in full. Email <strong>hello@wyreup.com</strong>
      from the address on your account with your order ID; refunds are
      processed back to the original payment instrument within 10
      business days.
    </p>

    <h2>Partial refunds</h2>
    <p>
      If you've used some but not all of the credits from a recent
      purchase, we will refund the pro-rated amount for the unused
      portion at the per-credit price you paid.
    </p>

    <h2>Used credits</h2>
    <p>
      Credits already consumed by a successful PRO tool run are not
      refundable. A successful run means the tool ran end-to-end and
      returned a result, regardless of whether the result was what you
      hoped for. AI model accuracy, output suitability for your
      specific purpose, and second-guessing the result after the fact
      are not grounds for a refund — see the warranty disclaimer in the
      <a href="/legal/terms">Terms of Service</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Exception:</strong> if a tool returned a clearly broken
      result due to our infrastructure failure (an internal error, a
      truncated response, a stack-trace where output should be), email
      <strong>hello@wyreup.com</strong> with the run ID from your
      account history and we will refund the credits used.
    </p>

    <h2>Failed runs are auto-refunded</h2>
    <p>
      If a PRO tool fails to complete (e.g. the model provider returns
      an error), we automatically refund the credits to your balance.
      No action needed — you'll see a "refund" entry in your account
      history. This is built into the platform, not a manual process.
    </p>

    <h2>Chargebacks</h2>
    <p>
      If you have a billing dispute, please email us first. Filing a
      chargeback before contacting us, when a refund would have been
      issued anyway, results in your account being suspended pending
      resolution because chargebacks carry fees that we cannot absorb at
      our pricing.
    </p>
    <p>
      A chargeback does not entitle you to retroactive refund of
      credits already consumed. Successful PRO tool runs that ran
      against the original purchase have been paid for by you to the
      hosted-AI provider via our infrastructure; those costs are not
      recoverable on our side. If a chargeback reverses a purchase
      whose credits were consumed, your account balance will reflect
      the resulting deficit and further PRO usage will be blocked until
      the deficit is settled or the chargeback is reversed.
    </p>

    <h2>Account closure</h2>
    <p>
      If you close your account, we refund any unused credits in your
      balance regardless of the 30-day window. Email
      <strong>hello@wyreup.com</strong> to close.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      Refund requests: <strong>hello@wyreup.com</strong>. Include your
      order ID (from the Lemon Squeezy receipt) and the email on your
      Wyreup account.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .legal {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-4) var(--space-12);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--text-primary);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  .legal h1 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl, 28px);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);
  }
  .legal h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-md);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-2);
  }
  .legal p,
  .legal ul {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
  }
  .meta {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--text-subtle);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
</style>
